00:13:58,080 --> 00:14:00,347
Stapley: Yeah. Schafer: Remember that? Stapley: Yeah.

225
00:14:00,347 --> 00:14:02,073
So is that how we're going to do it?

226
00:14:02,080 --> 00:14:05,046
Like I'm thinking of layers basically.

227
00:14:05,046 --> 00:14:08,841
Petty: The goal is just to get like a type of environment, you know.

228
00:14:08,841 --> 00:14:14,234
Like maybe it looks like something that the player could walk, kind of left or right and have it scroll or into.

229
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:16,140
Kind of either one we could explore.

230
00:14:16,140 --> 00:14:21,080
Schafer: Right now he's taking, you know, Bagel's work and Bagel's not a very technical person

231
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:23,980
so he just paints these awesome paintings.

232
00:14:23,980 --> 00:14:27,020
But then making it actually look good in the game is a whole different thing.

233
00:14:27,020 --> 00:14:34,460
And so we've got Lee working on actually making that a realized game playing world.

234
00:14:34,460 --> 00:14:38,327
And it's really fun to see them working together, because they're so different but they're putting together this, I think,

235
00:14:38,327 --> 00:14:41,220
awesome looking visual style.

236
00:14:42,060 --> 00:14:44,760
Schafer: There's a lot of cabins in here.

237
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:46,660
Petty: Hey, that'd be a good one, Tim. That cabin.

238
00:14:46,660 --> 00:14:51,080
So if you wanted the player walk into the screen there, like it's a little slightly different

239
00:14:51,080 --> 00:14:54,046
but similar to that whole circus sequence in Monkey one.

240
00:14:54,046 --> 00:14:58,440
You just walk into that and they can make a move up to that top shot basically.

241
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:01,399
Petty: We haven't designed in the actual characters yet for the game.

242
00:15:01,399 --> 00:15:04,466
Tim is still writing and coming up with exactly what the world is.

243
00:15:04,466 --> 00:15:10,446
So we just sort of picked a character out of one of Bagel's sketches and put it into the game.

244
00:15:10,446 --> 00:15:12,846
And we needed to do, you know, we just needed it to move around.

245
00:15:12,846 --> 00:15:15,340
So I just did some really quick animation on it.

246
00:15:15,340 --> 00:15:19,500
It's certainly not great animation but just to get it to kind of move around the world.

247
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:21,300
And follow the camera.

248
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:27,820
And so I think, you know, you kind of get a sense of, is how the camera might follow the player and kind of lag behind the player.

249
00:15:28,440 --> 00:15:30,133
How it might move around the screen.

250
00:15:30,133 --> 00:15:37,433
And you'll see that one of the things we're doing here with this character is that as he's in this canopy, he's kind of tinted green and darker.

251
00:15:37,433 --> 00:15:40,500
And as he emerges into the sun, here he becomes a little brighter.

252
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:44,360
And we don't really have, you know, any true lighting that's going to paint it into the painting,

253
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:50,819
but I'm doing some simple things where we're using like color gradients based on location of the world and kind of multiplying it in this character.

254
00:15:50,820 --> 00:15:53,253
Just with the goal of getting to feel part of that environment.

255
00:15:53,260 --> 00:15:58,087
And that's a type of trick that we could do technically in the game image if we wanted to.

256
00:15:58,087 --> 00:15:59,181
And it's really quick to do.

257
00:15:59,181 --> 00:16:01,541
But it's enough to help him harmonize with the environment.

258
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:13,033
Schafer: Please join me in welcoming Mr. Chris Remo to the company.

259
00:16:13,033 --> 00:16:20,840
[Applause] Schafer: Remo's our community manager.

260
00:16:20,840 --> 00:16:23,300
He's been here now for two weeks or so, ish.

261
00:16:23,300 --> 00:16:24,520
Chris, could you please stand up.

262
00:16:24,980 --> 00:16:31,560
[Laughter] Any questions about any of that stuff before we talk about projects?

263
00:16:31,560 --> 00:16:34,960
I'll give you the update on Double Fine Adventures, awesome game.

264
00:16:35,520 --> 00:16:42,060
I'm working on design stuff and we have a team actually working on tools and engine and visual,

265
00:16:42,560 --> 00:16:44,626
pre-visualization of what the art side will look like.

266
00:16:44,626 --> 00:16:49,126
And I'm putting together one of my deliverables for the milestone, in a couple weeks.

267
00:16:49,126 --> 00:16:50,306
It's like a story document and stuff.

268
00:16:50,306 --> 00:16:55,500
And at that point I'll be like probably sharing more info about the game with other people company-wide.

269
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:59,100
Rice: Well I mean, Tim's been doing brainstorming stuff for a while.

270
00:16:59,240 --> 00:17:04,947
And that's still what he's doing, just kind of holing up in his office and figuring out what the game is.

271
00:17:08,660 --> 00:17:11,425
Schafer: You know, at the very beginning I'm locked in my room a lot writing dialogue.

272
00:17:11,425 --> 00:17:16,453
But then I kind of have the job of pulling this whole thing down the road.

273
00:17:16,780 --> 00:17:19,013
You know, so I was ready to finally pitch to the team.

274
00:17:19,020 --> 00:17:21,819
I'm not really, haven't really felt right to pitch to the whole company yet.

275
00:17:21,819 --> 00:17:24,699
That'll come later but, so I pitched to the whole team.

276
00:17:24,700 --> 00:17:27,380
Schafer: OK. So I'm going to talk about the game today with everybody.

277
00:17:27,380 --> 00:17:31,040
And some people have heard about it and some people have not.

278
00:17:31,040 --> 00:17:32,640
Did I talk to you about the game?

279
00:17:33,540 --> 00:17:36,240
Some people have not, not just you.

280
00:17:36,240 --> 00:17:41,333
[Laughter] Petty: There're several people in Wisconsin.

281
00:17:41,333 --> 00:17:42,953
Schafer: As you see, I've made a lot of progress.

282
00:17:42,960 --> 00:17:46,480
I've designed some monster designs. Rice: I like it.

283
00:17:47,820 --> 00:17:53,440
Schafer: And then I was going to go and do some detail about some ideas for the beginning of one side of the story.

284
00:17:53,440 --> 00:17:58,200
Just 'cause the first example, like a sample game play and then we can all tear it apart

285
00:17:58,200 --> 00:18:00,520
and talk about how it's never, never, never going to work.

286
00:18:01,820 --> 00:18:03,920
Schafer: And it's an interesting process where...

287
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:10,680
deciding when to solicit feedback and when to actually sell.

288
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:13,713
It's like sometimes you're selling and sometimes looking for feedback.

289
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:20,960
And the idea... And early on I could sense like in the meeting, 'cause we talked about that as being a feedback session about the pitch and stuff.

290
00:18:21,140 --> 00:18:25,007
I realized I didn't want any feedback right then, like any in-depth feedback.

291
00:18:25,007 --> 00:18:30,926
So I kind of pitched the game and then kind of moved the meeting forward and ended it and because there is an early stage

292
00:18:30,926 --> 00:18:34,454
where you don't want any feedback because it doesn't really mean anything.

293
00:18:34,460 --> 00:18:39,487
Because they don't know still entirely what you're thinking and they might have an image in their head

294
00:18:39,487 --> 00:18:42,680
but it probably isn't exactly like what I have in my head.

295
00:18:42,680 --> 00:18:47,653
So I almost don't want their opinion of it because they're not talking about the thing I'm talking about.

296
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:50,460
They're talking about their own, how they see it.

297
00:18:50,460 --> 00:18:54,180
Offscreen Voice: Can I contribute as a devil's advocate?

298
00:18:55,466 --> 00:18:57,446
Schafer: I like where this is going.

299
00:18:57,446 --> 00:19:02,466
Remo: To me the strongest parts of this by far are the thematic aspects of the two characters in parallel.

300
00:19:02,466 --> 00:19:06,420
Especially switching between those, I think, could be incredibly important and really, really cool.

301
00:19:06,420 --> 00:19:13,580
Both in terms of game play and aesthetics and the stuff supporting that seems so high-concept to me that it might end up being top-heavy.

302
00:19:13,580 --> 00:19:18,740
Like it seems, it just seems like a really complicated thing.

303
00:19:19,940 --> 00:19:26,500
Schafer: People at, you know, at that meeting can bring up any sort of problems but it's just too early, you know.

304
00:19:30,120 --> 00:19:32,920
I dare them. Nice try, Chris Remo.

305
00:19:32,920 --> 00:19:34,987
What were we thinking inviting that guy to the meeting?

306
00:19:34,987 --> 00:19:39,100
Hey, maybe this thing you're doing shouldn't be done. Thanks.

307
00:19:39,620 --> 00:19:41,140
Remo: That's... I mean...

308
00:19:42,140 --> 00:19:46,760
Schafer: I guess because I see it working in my head, it isn't that complicated.

309
00:19:46,760 --> 00:19:53,466
I see that being like just providing a structure, actually, to how everything has to behave.

310
00:19:53,466 --> 00:19:58,406
Schafer: I do want is like when I say the idea, what other ideas that makes that person think of.

311
00:19:58,406 --> 00:20:00,700
Like you know what would be cool? And how they want to add to it.

312
00:20:00,700 --> 00:20:02,520
Petty: I love hearing new ideas.

313
00:20:02,520 --> 00:20:09,620
I like, Tim is a very, a lot of times Tim, the way he describes ideas is like, like the fact he described a box cover for a game

314
00:20:09,620 --> 00:20:11,787
that doesn't exist is a very Tim thing to do.

315
00:20:11,787 --> 00:20:16,540
Like he has, he's not an artist per se, like visual artist, but he thinks very visually.

316
00:20:16,540 --> 00:20:20,446
And I think that's helpful for someone like me and it's probably why we work so well together, is, you know,

317
00:20:20,446 --> 00:20:26,980
he's got these ideas and I can sort of, you know, as he's drawing out the birthday cakes and stuff like that

318
00:20:26,980 --> 00:20:28,000
I probably shouldn't talk about...

319
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,380
As he's drawing out some of the ideas on the white board in really simple fashion, I'm immediately starting to think about like,

320
00:20:33,380 --> 00:20:37,374
well, how's that going to put together in the space and how can we emphasize that or make that work.

321
00:20:37,380 --> 00:20:39,813
And so that's exciting to hear.

322
00:20:39,820 --> 00:20:42,353
Schafer: Anyway. So you pick which side you're on.

